      "text": "A 52-year-old man presents to the emergency department with 2 days of nausea, RUQ abdominal discomfort, and yellowing of the eyes. He was started on daily isoniazid plus rifampin for latent tuberculosis infection 8 weeks ago. He denies alcohol use and takes no other medications. Vital signs are temperature 37.0°C (98.6°F), heart rate 102 bpm, blood pressure 118/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and oxygen saturation 98% on room air. Physical examination is notable for jaundice, mild RUQ abdominal tenderness, mild confusion, and asterexis. Laboratory studies show alanine aminotransferase (ALT) 1549 U/L, aspartate aminotransferase (AST) 1234 U/L, alkaline phosphatase (ALP) 168 U/L, total bilirubin 13.4 mg/dL, international normalized ratio (INR) 2.4, albumin 31 g/L, and creatinine 1.0 mg/dL. Abdominal ultrasound shows no biliary obstruction. Viral hepatitis panel is negative. What is the most appropriate next step in management?",
